data.files#files():
You can get a list of files using the files() query.Access management: The query returns all files that are accessible for the
current user.Associations: You can use the filters to find files which are associated with other objects;
see createFileAssociation(). The typical flow looks loke this: First, you fetch the ID of an
object from your database and then query the related
files. For instance, the query shown below requests all files that are associated with a specific "contract".Visibility: For files marked as ‚Äúpublic‚Äù, the returned URL is static. If the file is marked as ‚Äúprivate‚Äù, then
the
URL is
referred to as a signed URL which is created for only one purpose. A signed URL works only for a short amount of time
and is not intended to be published.


query {
files(filter: {
entityName: {
equalTo: "contract"
},
entityIdentifiers: {
equalTo:"123"
}}) {
data {
id
name
contentType
url
isPublic
}
}
}



Parameter	Type	Description	entityName	object	Name of the object. This could be the name of the table in your database, e.g. "contract"	entityIdentifiers	object	References (or IDs) of the related objects from your database

data.file#file():
To download a single file, you can use the file() query.


query {
file(fileId: "123") {
id
name
url
isPublic
}
}

data.createfileupload#createFileUpload():
To upload file via API you need to proceed the following steps. However, it's recommended to use ROQ's File Upload UI
component instead of building it yourself.
Generate a signed URL using the createFileUpload() API
Upload file via the signed URL
Set status of the file using the updateFileStatus() API

The createFileUpload API returns a "signed URL" which is then used to upload the file directly from the user's browser
to the object storage.


mutation {
createFileUpload(
file: {
name: "abc123"
contentType: "image/png"
fileCategory: "xyz789"
}
) {
id
uploadUrl
}
}




Parameter	Type	Description	name	string	Name of the uploaded file	contentType	string	Mime type of the file, see here for a list of all types	fileCategory	string	Key of the category of the file
With the returned URL you can upload the file, for instance using curl:
curl 'https://s3.fr-par.scw.cloud/<bucket-name>' \
-H 'authority: s3.fr-par.scw.cloud' \
-H 'accept: application/json, text/plain, */*' \
-H 'accept-language: en-US,en;q=0.9' \
-H 'content-type: image/png' \
-H 'sec-fetch-mode: cors' \
-H 'sec-fetch-site: cross-site' \
--data-raw $'---REMOVED---' \
--compressed
When the upload is finished, you need to set the status of the upload. This is needed because the file is uploaded
directly to the object storage and therefore bypasses ROQ Platform.


mutation{
updateFileStatus(
fileId: "123",
status: READY
){
id
}
}

data.createfileassociation#createFileAssociat:
This endpoint is only available from the server side of your application.
Files usually belong to some other object. For instance, you may have PDFs which represent "contracts". Or you may
have images which are "avatars" and so on. To simplify this, ROQ enables you to relate files with objects which are
saved on your database. The advantage is that you don't need to add these relations to your own database.


mutation {
createFileAssociation(
createFileAssociationDto: {
entityReference: 4
entityName: "xyz789"
fileId: "4"
}
) {
id
}
}



Parameter	Type	Description	fileId	string	UUID of the file	entityReference	string	Reference (or ID) of the related entity in your database	entityName	string	Name of the object. This could be the name of the table in your database, e.g. "contract"

